Klobuchar endorsement of Biden

A couple of thoughts: 1) Klobuchar may have dropped out in part because she thinks Bernie could beat her at home which would be damaging to her career, maybe; and 2) Klobuchar's endorsement of Biden will help. I'm going to assume that more of the Klobuchar voters are pro-Biden rather than pro Bernie. Still I think Bernie has an edge.

Sanders was polling at a strong second, so taking just a sliver of Klobuchar's votes should tip him over. Some people will still vote for her given the announcement was so late and they may not know, and I think Biden will finish a strong second as the centrist vote coalesces around him -many conservative/Republican-leaning and centrist Democrats who would have voted for Klobuchar will shift to the more natural candidate, Biden and her backing, though late, will help, at least in the delegate count.
Klobuchar just hit the silk and will endorse Biden. The clown car is emptying pretty fast now; probably lose more on Wednesday.

Amy Klobuchar dropped out of the race. I assume her name will still appear on the ballot and she could still get votes. Since Senator Klobuchar dropped out, the two main candidates appear to be Bernie Sanders and Joe Biden. Bernie Sanders won the Minnesota primary in 2016 with a much bigger margin over Hillary Clinton (Bernie Sanders: 61.69%, Hillary Clinton: 38.31%). I have a feeling that Bernie Sanders will win the Minnesota primary.
Changed slightly after bad press because of a protest shutting down her rally in Minnesota.
Strong, popular home state Senator. She’s got this.
Adjusting in light of Buttigieg dropping out.

With Buttigieg out Klobuchar should just about get the edge from that, though perhaps with Biden gaining 'momentum' (I don't actually believe in political momentum in 99% of cases) he will 'steal' enough votes from her to give it to Sanders. Sanders did do very well here last time, but it is Klobuchar's home state, and they are polling close, so I expect it will be a close result either way.
I'm in too many of these Dem primary questions and my errors are correlated. So time to hedge. Hedge Amy.

we finally got a Minnesota poll that shows Klobuchar ahead, but factoring in momentum I still have Bernie as a slight favourite: there's also a decent chance (30-40%) that Klobuchar drops out before Super Tuesday anyway.

The latest polls to show Klobuchar ahead of Bernie, but not too far ahead, the biggest question will be will Klobuchar and Warren (also nest some significant support in Minnesota) stay in the race till Super Tuesday. It is far more likely that Warren will stick it through till Super Tuesday, but after a lackluster showing in Nevada and a predictable bad showing in South Carolina and no guaranteed victory in her home state, Klobuchar may retire early, in which case, as was the case in 2016 it is more than likely that Bernie will win Minnesota.

I think Sanders focus on Social Economic Issues will play well in this state. I think Mayor Pete will win over a lot of younger professional voters and I think Michal Bloomberg will win over moderates. Klobuchar will have her best race here because this is her home state.
Amy Klobichar is from Minnesota and a Democratic Senator. I think she has the best chance.
Amy's home state gives a fighting chance
We love Amy here in the North Star State

a very even probability split for Minnesota. Virtually no polling and no recent polling at this time. It's Klobuchar's home state, hence her elevated chances in this place specifically. Bernie beat Hillary comfortably here (61/38) in 2016, and Obama also beat Hillary here easily in 2008. So I guess the electorate probably skews more liberal, which makes me push Biden, Buttigeig & Bloomberg all a bit lower than I have them for other Super Tuesday states at the moment.
There is no prediction market for this primary. Considering the high popularity of Amy in her own state of MN, I give her a higher probability than the crowd forecast.
Most recent poll is from Nov 2019, from Kaiser Family Fnd posted on 538 and gave Warren 10 pts up. Things have changed a lot since.

With no updated polls in Minnesota, it is impossible to make a statistical analysis of the Minnesota Primary. However, based on judgment the primary race will be between Klobuchar and Bernie. Minnesota is inclined to vote more progressive as voted for Bernie in 2016, however, Klobuchar as the state senator hold a major advantage in Minnesota and will likely capturing the vast majority of moderate voters and other less political voters. Therefore it'll be hard for Bernie to rally enough support to overtake Klobuchar hometown advantage and will the campaign will likely not do as much organizing there because of it. Therefore, it isn't unlikely that Bernie will win, but it would be an upset.
Updating to reflect Klobuchar potentially having a strong base of support in MN. Question is, does that reflect the state's current opinion?

An initial, intuitive, gut-check forecast. Will adjust with subsequent research. If so, let us know! I'm presuming the outcome will be closer to the current national trend... but there is a lot of old press on Warren. Any thoughts?
